      <item>
        <title>3 useful ways to use Wget</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;GNUâ€™s &lt;code&gt;wget&lt;/code&gt; is a command line tool to download files over HTTP(S) and FTP.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While &lt;code&gt;curl&lt;/code&gt; is great to send custom requests, it lacks a recursive mode to download all the resources linked to a page or domain.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is where Wget is much useful.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-shell&quot; data-lang=&quot;shell&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# Copy a whole site locally,&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# including images, css, js&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# and converting links&lt;/span&gt;
wget -p -m -k fullwebâ€‹.io
 
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# Check for 404 links&lt;/span&gt;
wget --spider your-url-list.txt
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# give it an HTML page with -F&lt;/span&gt;
wget --spider -F you-webpage.html
 
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# Accept (-A) or reject (-R) some files&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# here only keeping images from the site&lt;/span&gt;
wget -p -A png,jpg,jpeg,gif &lt;span class=&quot;se&quot;&gt;\ &lt;/span&gt;
        -R html,css,js &lt;span class=&quot;se&quot;&gt;\ &lt;/span&gt;
        wikipediaâ€‹.org&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

</description>
