      <item>
        <title>Network Power Tool: netcat</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Ever heard of &lt;code&gt;netcat&lt;/code&gt;? Itâ€™s a small network utility to create TCP and UDP connections.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Leâ€™s see how to transfer files with it:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-shell&quot; data-lang=&quot;shell&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# Simple file transfer over network:&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# run the server with&lt;/span&gt;
nc -l 8000 &amp;gt; file_you_receive
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# send the file on the client with&lt;/span&gt;
cat file_you_send | nc server_ip 8000
 
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# Getting fancy, transferring lots of&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# small/medium files efficiently:&lt;/span&gt;
tar -cf - . | pigz | nc -l 8000
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# On the receiving machine:&lt;/span&gt;
nc server_ip 8000 &amp;gt; all_your_files.tar.gz
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# (pigz is a parallel gzip)&lt;/span&gt;
 
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# By default netcat uses TCP,&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;# use UDP with -u&lt;/span&gt;
netcat -u -l 8000&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

</description>
